# How the work was done

## Case study: the 840 ms to 120 ms latency cut
The authorization path made a blocking call to a third-party fraud scorer that
averaged 600 ms and spiked to 2 seconds. Rather than wait, I changed the flow:

1. **Speculate.** Authorize optimistically against a local risk model (8 ms)
   and release the hold immediately, with a hard 50 ms budget.
2. **Reconcile.** Fire the slow fraud check asynchronously; if it later
   disagrees, reverse via the ledger (see [[z=1|the ledger work]]).
3. **Cap the blast radius.** Speculative auth only applies under a per-merchant
   risk ceiling, so a bad model never exposes more than a bounded dollar amount.

Result: p99 dropped from 840 ms to 120 ms, chargebacks rose by less than 0.02
percent, and throughput went from 4k to 13k authorizations per second on the
same hardware.

## Case study: killing double charges with an append-only ledger
The old system stored balances as mutable rows, so a retried request could
apply a charge twice. I modeled every money movement as an immutable event
keyed by a client-supplied idempotency token. Replaying events became the
source of truth; balances became a derived, cacheable projection.

- 30+ double-charge incidents per year went to zero in the 18 months after.
- Reconciliation that took a nightly 4-hour batch became a streaming view.

## How I lead
- I write the postmortem myself when I am the incident commander, blameless and
  specific, with one owned action item per contributing cause.
- I pair with new hires for their first two on-call shifts before they solo.

